{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17658052","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17658052"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:40:37+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:40:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20701"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20701","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20701"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.67,0.1,0.1,0.1,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13577"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95064"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13577","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13577"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20701"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78031"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11587"},{"type":"tags","id":"11588"},{"type":"tags","id":"12578"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32632"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32633"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95064","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/95064"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best explains the primary pathophysiological mechanism of oedema formation in nephrotic syndrome?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Reduced plasma oncotic pressure due to hypoalbuminaemia","Activation of the renin-angiotensin-aldosterone system","Increased glomerular capillary permeability to proteins","Decreased glomerular filtration rate","Impaired tubular reabsorption of sodium"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary mechanism causing oedema in nephrotic syndrome is \u003Cstrong\u003Ereduced plasma oncotic pressure due to hypoalbuminaemia\u003C/strong\u003E. According to Starling forces, fluid movement across capillary membranes depends on the balance between hydrostatic pressure (pushing fluid out of vessels) and oncotic pressure (pulling fluid into vessels). Albumin normally accounts for almost half of the total plasma protein and is the main contributor to plasma oncotic pressure. When albumin levels fall significantly, the oncotic pressure decreases, allowing fluid to leak into the interstitial spaces, resulting in generalised oedema.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActivation of the renin-angiotensin-aldosterone system\u003C/strong\u003E - This is a secondary mechanism in nephrotic syndrome that contributes to oedema formation. The reduced effective circulating volume due to hypoalbuminaemia triggers this system, leading to sodium and water retention, but it is not the primary mechanism.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased glomerular capillary permeability to proteins\u003C/strong\u003E - This is the underlying cause of proteinuria in nephrotic syndrome, which leads to hypoalbuminaemia, but is not directly responsible for oedema formation.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased glomerular filtration rate\u003C/strong\u003E - While this can occur in some cases of nephrotic syndrome, particularly with progression to chronic kidney disease, this is not the primary mechanism of oedema.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImpaired tubular reabsorption of sodium\u003C/strong\u003E - In nephrotic syndrome, tubular sodium reabsorption is actually increased rather than impaired, due to activation of the renin-angiotensin-aldosterone system.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn nephrotic syndrome, the sequence of events typically involves: increased glomerular permeability to proteins \u2192 proteinuria \u2192 hypoalbuminaemia \u2192 reduced plasma oncotic pressure \u2192 oedema. Secondary mechanisms include activation of the renin-angiotensin-aldosterone system, which further contributes to sodium and water retention.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Starling forces govern fluid movement across capillary membranes, with oncotic pressure opposing hydrostatic pressure.","Hypoalbuminaemia reduces plasma oncotic pressure, disrupting the balance of Starling forces and promoting fluid movement into interstitial spaces.","Nephrotic syndrome causes significant proteinuria leading to hypoalbuminaemia and subsequent oedema.","Secondary sodium retention in nephrotic syndrome occurs via activation of the renin-angiotensin-aldosterone system in response to reduced effective circulating volume."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 4; page 116."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78031"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20701"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78031","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/78031"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-27T08:45:16+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-27T08:47:54+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13577"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95064"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}}